[{"sha":"f063af772cbc94c6f0880f6a74aca096e31c63a7","author":{"email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org","name":"A. Unique TensorFlower"},"message":"Consider the following instance of mhlo.reduce operation

%retval = "mhlo.reduce"(%a, %b) ( {
 ^bb0(%arg1: tensor<i32>, %arg2: tensor<i32>):  // no predecessors
     %t = mhlo.maximum %arg1, %arg2 : tensor<i32>
      "mhlo.return"(%t) : (tensor<i32>) -> ()
 }) {dimensions = dense<0> : tensor<1xi64>} : (tensor<nxi32>, tensor<i32>) -> tensor<i32>

In the example above, the only useful semantic information conveyed by the region inside the mhlo.reduce operation is that the reduction is based on maximum. We can instead pretty-print the above to

%retval = mhlo.reduce(%a, %b) applies mhlo.maximum across dimensions =  [0] : (tensor<nxi32>, tensor<i32>) -> tensor<i32>

Such succinct pretty printing is currently enabled based on the following simplifying assumptions:

1. The reduce-op wraps a single inner-op in the associated region.
2. The inner-op is one of mhlo::AddOp, mhlo::MaxOp or mhlo::MinOp.
3. The reduce-op consist of at least one input-operand; The operand-types of
   inner-op should be derived trivially from the element-type of reduce-op's
   first input-operand.
4: The  arguments of the region's only basic block are forwarded perfectly
   to inner-op's operands.
5. The reduce-op, inner-op, blocks arguments, and the return-op all have the
   same location.
6. The single operation result is perfectly forwarded to the reduce op
   return.
